('chunk_7c009a24a8f32527be','file_2060df81d599553cd9','chemistry.md','Cross-Subject Connections','- **Physics**: Atomic structure, subatomic charge and mass, and radioactive decay link directly to Physics topics on the atom, radiation, and energy transfer (exothermic/endothermic reactions and conservation laws mirror conservation of energy).
- **Biology**: Ions such as sodium, potassium and chloride drive nerve impulses; carbon-14 dating and radioisotope imaging connect to human biology and evolution; separation techniques underpin analysing biological samples (chromatography of pigments in leaves).
- **Mathematics**: Calculating Rf values (ratios and division), balancing equations (whole-number ratios and simplest form), the crisscross method (lowest common multiples and simplifying), and interpreting data tables and graphs of reactivity and boiling points all use core maths skills.','{"cross":1,"subject":1,"connections":1,"physics":2,"atomic":1,"structure":1,"subatomic":1,"charge":1,"and":13,"mass":1,"radioactive":1,"decay":1,"link":1,"directly":1,"topics":1,"the":2,"atom":1,"radiation":1,"energy":2,"transfer":1,"exothermic":1,"endothermic":1,"reactions":1,"conservation":2,"laws":1,"mirror":1,"biology":2,"ions":1,"such":1,"sodium":1,"potassium":1,"chloride":1,"drive":1,"nerve":1,"impulses":1,"carbon":1,"dating":1,"radioisotope":1,"imaging":1,"connect":1,"human":1,"evolution":1,"separation":1,"techniques":1,"underpin":1,"analysing":1,"biological":1,"samples":1,"chromatography":1,"pigments":1,"leaves":1,"mathematics":1,"calculating":1,"values":1,"ratios":2,"division":1,"balancing":1,"equations":1,"whole":1,"number":1,"simplest":1,"form":1,"crisscross":1,"method":1,"lowest":1,"common":1,"multiples":1,"simplifying":1,"interpreting":1,"data":1,"tables":1,"graphs":1,"reactivity":1,"boiling":1,"points":1,"all":1,"use":1,"core":1,"maths":1,"skills":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_43f16b9a40f3a9b6d6','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Subject Overview','Digital Design at IISH sits in the **MYP Design** subject group. Grade 7 students learn to solve real-life problems by moving through the **MYP Design Cycle**, a structured, iterative process for turning a need into a working product. The course is delivered through two application units across the year:

- **Unit 1 — Toy and Game Design** (July–December)
- **Unit 2 — Robotics (Maker Bot)** (January–May)

For each unit students produce an **e-Portfolio**: a digital document (Google Doc/Slides, PDF, or website) that captures their thinking and evidence at every stage of the Design Cycle for a real-life scenario. The e-Portfolio *is* the assessment — it shows the journey, not just the finished product.','{"subject":2,"overview":1,"digital":2,"design":5,"iish":1,"sits":1,"the":9,"myp":2,"group":1,"grade":1,"students":2,"learn":1,"solve":1,"real":2,"life":2,"problems":1,"moving":1,"through":2,"cycle":2,"structured":1,"iterative":1,"process":1,"for":3,"turning":1,"need":1,"into":1,"working":1,"product":2,"course":1,"delivered":1,"two":1,"application":1,"units":1,"across":1,"year":1,"unit":3,"toy":1,"and":2,"game":1,"july":1,"december":1,"robotics":1,"maker":1,"bot":1,"january":1,"may":1,"each":1,"produce":1,"portfolio":2,"document":1,"google":1,"doc":1,"slides":1,"pdf":1,"website":1,"that":1,"captures":1,"their":1,"thinking":1,"evidence":1,"every":1,"stage":1,"scenario":1,"assessment":1,"shows":1,"journey":1,"not":1,"just":1,"finished":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_4bf73359e97cf8c4d2','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','The Four MYP Design Criteria','MYP Design is assessed against four criteria, each scored out of 8. In Grade 7 these are taught in order but revisited iteratively.

| Criterion | Name | Core question | Grade 7 focus |
|-----------|------|---------------|---------------|
| **A** | Inquiring and Analysing | *What is the problem and what already exists?* | Identify a problem, research it, analyse existing products |
| **B** | Developing Ideas | *What could the solution look like?* | Success criteria, design ideas/diagrams, flowchart |
| **C** | Creating the Solution | *Can I build it?* | Logical plan, make the product, record changes |
| **D** | Evaluating | *Does it work and what is its impact?* | Test cases, testing against success criteria, improvements, client impact |','{"the":5,"four":2,"myp":2,"design":3,"criteria":4,"assessed":1,"against":2,"each":1,"scored":1,"out":1,"grade":2,"these":1,"are":1,"taught":1,"order":1,"but":1,"revisited":1,"iteratively":1,"criterion":1,"name":1,"core":1,"question":1,"focus":1,"inquiring":1,"and":3,"analysing":1,"what":4,"problem":2,"already":1,"exists":1,"identify":1,"research":1,"analyse":1,"existing":1,"products":1,"developing":1,"ideas":2,"could":1,"solution":2,"look":1,"like":1,"success":2,"diagrams":1,"flowchart":1,"creating":1,"can":1,"build":1,"logical":1,"plan":1,"make":1,"product":1,"record":1,"changes":1,"evaluating":1,"does":1,"work":1,"its":1,"impact":2,"test":1,"cases":1,"testing":1,"improvements":1,"client":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_e7fd1f26fc571939e6','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Design-Related Concepts','Related concepts are the "lenses" that sharpen inquiry in Design. Students should be able to name and use these:

- **Function** — what the product does and how well.
- **Form** — the shape, look and structure of the product.
- **Innovation** — new or improved ideas that add value.
- **Evaluation** — judging quality against criteria.
- **Ergonomics** — designing to fit the human user comfortably and safely.
- **Adaptation** — adjusting a design for a new context or user.
- **Collaboration** — working with clients, users and teammates.
- **Markets and trends** — what users want and what is popular now.
- **Resources** — the materials, tools, time and skills available.
- **Sustainability** — designing with care for people and the planet.
- **Perspective** — considering different viewpoints and needs.','{"design":3,"related":2,"concepts":2,"are":1,"the":7,"lenses":1,"that":2,"sharpen":1,"inquiry":1,"students":1,"should":1,"able":1,"name":1,"and":10,"use":1,"these":1,"function":1,"what":3,"product":2,"does":1,"how":1,"well":1,"form":1,"shape":1,"look":1,"structure":1,"innovation":1,"new":2,"improved":1,"ideas":1,"add":1,"value":1,"evaluation":1,"judging":1,"quality":1,"against":1,"criteria":1,"ergonomics":1,"designing":2,"fit":1,"human":1,"user":2,"comfortably":1,"safely":1,"adaptation":1,"adjusting":1,"for":2,"context":1,"collaboration":1,"working":1,"with":2,"clients":1,"users":2,"teammates":1,"markets":1,"trends":1,"want":1,"popular":1,"now":1,"resources":1,"materials":1,"tools":1,"time":1,"skills":1,"available":1,"sustainability":1,"care":1,"people":1,"planet":1,"perspective":1,"considering":1,"different":1,"viewpoints":1,"needs":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_4d2add1aad4eacbd6d','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','The Design Cycle (Iterative, Not Linear)','The Design Cycle is a **loop**, not a straight line. Students inquire (A), develop ideas (B), create (C) and evaluate (D) — and the evaluation feeds back into new inquiry. Testing in D often sends a designer *back* to B or C to improve the product. Good designers circle around the cycle several times.

| Stage | Criterion | Key output in the e-Portfolio |
|-------|-----------|-------------------------------|
| Inquiring & Analysing | A | Problem statement, research, product analysis, SWOT |
| Developing Ideas | B | Success criteria, design diagrams, chosen design, flowchart |
| Creating the Solution | C | Logical plan, the built product, list of changes |
| Evaluating | D | Test cases, test results, improvements, client impact |','{"the":8,"design":4,"cycle":3,"iterative":1,"not":2,"linear":1,"loop":1,"straight":1,"line":1,"students":1,"inquire":1,"develop":1,"ideas":2,"create":1,"and":2,"evaluate":1,"evaluation":1,"feeds":1,"back":2,"into":1,"new":1,"inquiry":1,"testing":1,"often":1,"sends":1,"designer":1,"improve":1,"product":3,"good":1,"designers":1,"circle":1,"around":1,"several":1,"times":1,"stage":1,"criterion":1,"key":1,"output":1,"portfolio":1,"inquiring":1,"analysing":1,"problem":1,"statement":1,"research":1,"analysis":1,"swot":1,"developing":1,"success":1,"criteria":1,"diagrams":1,"chosen":1,"flowchart":1,"creating":1,"solution":1,"logical":1,"plan":1,"built":1,"list":1,"changes":1,"evaluating":1,"test":2,"cases":1,"results":1,"improvements":1,"client":1,"impact":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_16e14c0ff4ad95519a','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','The e-Portfolio Requirement','- One e-Portfolio per unit, organised by criterion (A → B → C → D).
- Every claim needs **evidence**: screenshots, photos, survey data, diagrams, links.
- Written in the student''s own words, with a **bibliography** for sources.
- Shows iteration — including mistakes, changes and improvements. Struggles that are documented and fixed score higher than a polished product with no visible process.

---','{"the":2,"portfolio":2,"requirement":1,"one":1,"per":1,"unit":1,"organised":1,"criterion":1,"every":1,"claim":1,"needs":1,"evidence":1,"screenshots":1,"photos":1,"survey":1,"data":1,"diagrams":1,"links":1,"written":1,"student":1,"own":1,"words":1,"with":2,"bibliography":1,"for":1,"sources":1,"shows":1,"iteration":1,"including":1,"mistakes":1,"changes":1,"and":2,"improvements":1,"struggles":1,"that":1,"are":1,"documented":1,"fixed":1,"score":1,"higher":1,"than":1,"polished":1,"product":1,"visible":1,"process":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_5b2ed6bcf091fa5baa','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Design-Cycle Framework — Inquiry Planning','**Key Concept:** Communities (design serves real people and clients).
**Related Concepts:** Function, Evaluation, Collaboration.
**Global Context:** Identities and relationships (how products meet human needs).
**Statement of Inquiry:** *Designers who understand the needs of a community can evaluate and refine functional solutions that improve people''s lives.*

**Inquiry questions**
- *Factual:* What are the four stages of the MYP Design Cycle?
- *Conceptual:* Why is the Design Cycle iterative rather than linear?
- *Debatable:* Is understanding the user more important than technical skill when designing a product?

---','{"design":4,"cycle":3,"framework":1,"inquiry":3,"planning":1,"key":1,"concept":1,"communities":1,"serves":1,"real":1,"people":2,"and":3,"clients":1,"related":1,"concepts":1,"function":1,"evaluation":1,"collaboration":1,"global":1,"context":1,"identities":1,"relationships":1,"how":1,"products":1,"meet":1,"human":1,"needs":2,"statement":1,"designers":1,"who":1,"understand":1,"the":5,"community":1,"can":1,"evaluate":1,"refine":1,"functional":1,"solutions":1,"that":1,"improve":1,"lives":1,"questions":1,"factual":1,"what":1,"are":1,"four":1,"stages":1,"myp":1,"conceptual":1,"why":1,"iterative":1,"rather":1,"than":2,"linear":1,"debatable":1,"understanding":1,"user":1,"more":1,"important":1,"technical":1,"skill":1,"when":1,"designing":1,"product":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c2f1eeb5242c64cec4','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','CRITERION A — Inquiring and Analysing','Criterion A is about **understanding the problem before building anything**. Students identify a real problem, prove it is worth solving, learn about the user, and study what already exists.','{"criterion":2,"inquiring":1,"and":2,"analysing":1,"about":2,"understanding":1,"the":2,"problem":2,"before":1,"building":1,"anything":1,"students":1,"identify":1,"real":1,"prove":1,"worth":1,"solving":1,"learn":1,"user":1,"study":1,"what":1,"already":1,"exists":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_d21141f492c17c7bd4','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Problem Identification','**Definition:** Clearly stating a real-life problem or need that a design can solve, and justifying *why* a solution is required.

**How to do it (checklist):**
1. Describe the situation or scenario.
2. Name who is affected (the client/user).
3. State the problem in one clear sentence.
4. Justify *why* it matters — what happens if it is not solved?
5. Explain why a design solution (a product) is the right response.

**Worked mini-example (Toy/Game):** *"Younger students at IISH (ages 5–7) in after-school care often wait with nothing to do. A problem is that there is no simple, safe indoor game they can play in small groups without adult setup. A solution is needed because boredom leads to restlessness and conflict; a well-designed board or card game would keep them engaged and build turn-taking skills."*

**Why it matters:** A weak problem statement produces a solution nobody needs. Everything downstream (research, criteria, testing) points back to the problem.

**Common misconception:** *"The problem is just the product I want to make."* Correction: the problem is the **need**, stated independently of any solution. "We need a robot" is not a problem; "elderly residents forget to water their plants" is.

**Command-term questions:**
- **State** the problem your design will solve. (1 sentence)
- **Explain** why a solution to this problem is needed. (justify with a consequence)','{"problem":11,"identification":1,"definition":1,"clearly":1,"stating":1,"real":1,"life":1,"need":3,"that":2,"design":3,"can":2,"solve":2,"and":3,"justifying":1,"why":5,"solution":6,"required":1,"how":1,"checklist":1,"describe":1,"the":10,"situation":1,"scenario":1,"name":1,"who":1,"affected":1,"client":1,"user":1,"state":2,"one":1,"clear":1,"sentence":2,"justify":2,"matters":2,"what":1,"happens":1,"not":2,"solved":1,"explain":2,"product":2,"right":1,"response":1,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"toy":1,"game":3,"younger":1,"students":1,"iish":1,"ages":1,"after":1,"school":1,"care":1,"often":1,"wait":1,"with":2,"nothing":1,"there":1,"simple":1,"safe":1,"indoor":1,"they":1,"play":1,"small":1,"groups":1,"without":1,"adult":1,"setup":1,"needed":2,"because":1,"boredom":1,"leads":1,"restlessness":1,"conflict":1,"well":1,"designed":1,"board":1,"card":1,"would":1,"keep":1,"them":1,"engaged":1,"build":1,"turn":1,"taking":1,"skills":1,"weak":1,"statement":1,"produces":1,"nobody":1,"needs":1,"everything":1,"downstream":1,"research":1,"criteria":1,"testing":1,"points":1,"back":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"just":1,"want":1,"make":1,"correction":1,"stated":1,"independently":1,"any":1,"robot":1,"elderly":1,"residents":1,"forget":1,"water":1,"their":1,"plants":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"your":1,"will":1,"this":1,"consequence":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_b2b9cb53a779283841','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Target Audience','**Definition:** The specific group of people the product is designed for.

**How to do it:**
1. Name the group (age, role, context).
2. Describe their needs, abilities and limits.
3. Keep it **specific** — "children" is too broad; "IISH students aged 5–7 in after-school care" is usable.

**Worked mini-example (Robotics):** Target audience = *"Home gardeners aged 30–55 who travel for work and own 4–6 potted plants indoors."* This tells us the Maker Bot must be simple, safe near soil/water, and usable without coding knowledge.

**Why it matters:** The audience determines the success criteria and the testing. You cannot judge "easy to use" without knowing *for whom*.

**Common misconception:** *"Everyone is my audience."* Correction: designing for everyone means designing for no one. Narrow the audience so decisions become clear.

**Command-term question:** **Identify** your target audience and **describe** two of their needs.','{"target":3,"audience":6,"definition":1,"the":8,"specific":2,"group":2,"people":1,"product":1,"designed":1,"for":5,"how":1,"name":1,"age":1,"role":1,"context":1,"describe":2,"their":2,"needs":2,"abilities":1,"and":5,"limits":1,"keep":1,"children":1,"too":1,"broad":1,"iish":1,"students":1,"aged":2,"after":1,"school":1,"care":1,"usable":2,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":1,"robotics":1,"home":1,"gardeners":1,"who":1,"travel":1,"work":1,"own":1,"potted":1,"plants":1,"indoors":1,"this":1,"tells":1,"maker":1,"bot":1,"must":1,"simple":1,"safe":1,"near":1,"soil":1,"water":1,"without":2,"coding":1,"knowledge":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"determines":1,"success":1,"criteria":1,"testing":1,"you":1,"cannot":1,"judge":1,"easy":1,"use":1,"knowing":1,"whom":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"everyone":2,"correction":1,"designing":2,"means":1,"one":1,"narrow":1,"decisions":1,"become":1,"clear":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"identify":1,"your":1,"two":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_e5b75900e23bed4138','file_2567f8311bd711b854','digital-design.md','Primary vs Secondary Research','**Definition:**
- **Primary research** — data you collect yourself, first-hand (surveys, interviews, observations, your own testing).
- **Secondary research** — information gathered by others that you find (websites, books, articles, videos, existing product reviews).

**How to do it (checklist):**
1. Plan *what* you need to know.
2. Choose primary methods to hear directly from users.
3. Choose secondary methods to understand the wider context and existing solutions.
4. Record the **source** of every piece of information.

| Type | Examples | Strength | Limit |
|------|----------|----------|-------|
| Primary | Survey of classmates, interview with a teacher, observation | Directly about *your* users | Takes time; small sample |
| Secondary | Website on board-game design, robot sensor datasheet | Fast, broad, expert | May be outdated or not about your users |

**Worked mini-example (Toy/Game):** Primary = a survey asking 20 younger students which game types they enjoy. Secondary = an article on age-appropriate game mechanics for 5–7 year-olds.

**Why it matters:** Good design balances *what real users say* (primary) with *what is already known* (secondary).

**Common misconception:** *"Anything on the internet is primary research because I found it."* Correction: if someone else produced it, it is **secondary**, no matter how you accessed it.

**Command-term question:** **Distinguish** between primary and secondary research using an example from your project.','{"primary":8,"secondary":8,"research":5,"definition":1,"data":1,"you":4,"collect":1,"yourself":1,"first":1,"hand":1,"surveys":1,"interviews":1,"observations":1,"your":4,"own":1,"testing":1,"information":2,"gathered":1,"others":1,"that":1,"find":1,"websites":1,"books":1,"articles":1,"videos":1,"existing":2,"product":1,"reviews":1,"how":2,"checklist":1,"plan":1,"what":3,"need":1,"know":1,"choose":2,"methods":2,"hear":1,"directly":2,"from":2,"users":4,"understand":1,"the":3,"wider":1,"context":1,"and":2,"solutions":1,"record":1,"source":1,"every":1,"piece":1,"type":1,"examples":1,"strength":1,"limit":1,"survey":2,"classmates":1,"interview":1,"with":2,"teacher":1,"observation":1,"about":2,"takes":1,"time":1,"small":1,"sample":1,"website":1,"board":1,"game":4,"design":2,"robot":1,"sensor":1,"datasheet":1,"fast":1,"broad":1,"expert":1,"may":1,"outdated":1,"not":1,"worked":1,"mini":1,"example":2,"toy":1,"asking":1,"younger":1,"students":1,"which":1,"types":1,"they":1,"enjoy":1,"article":1,"age":1,"appropriate":1,"mechanics":1,"for":1,"year":1,"olds":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"good":1,"balances":1,"real":1,"say":1,"already":1,"known":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"anything":1,"internet":1,"because":1,"found":1,"correction":1,"someone":1,"else":1,"produced":1,"matter":1,"accessed":1,"command":1,"term":1,"question":1,"distinguish":1,"between":1,"using":1,"project":1}'::jsonb);